  <description type="morphology">Plants large. Stems 5–16 cm. Leaves with distalmost spiraled around stem, catenulate, spreading, distant, broadly ovate-lanceolate, sometimes falcate, pluriplicate. Capsule 2.5–3.5 mm.</description>
  <description type="phenology">Capsules mature Jun-Sep.</description>
  <description type="habitat">Seeps, exposed slopes, mountain meadows;</description>
  <description type="elevation">low to high elevations (0-3000 m);</description>
  <description type="distribution">Alta., B.C., N.B., Ont., Que.; Alaska, Calif., Colo., Idaho, N.Y., Oreg., Utah, Wash.</description>
  <discussion>Variety americana, which includes the largest plants of the genus in North America, can be recognized by its robust habit, distant, catenulate leaves, and distalmost leaves spiraled around the stem.</discussion>
